english:
  title: A Record of the Miraculous Manifestations of the Buddha Relics at Gukcheongsa Temple's Golden Hall
  author: Min Ji
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Way of Kings knows no duality, yet the rites and music of the Five Emperors and Three Kings differ—because the ages they encountered were sometimes ordered and sometimes chaotic. The Buddha Vehicle is singular, yet the expedient and ultimate teachings at Deer Park and Vulture Peak differ—because the opportunities they awaited were sometimes small and sometimes great. Though the laws of the human king and the dharma king emerge in different eras, in their union as sovereignty and in their convergence as Buddhahood, they are not so far apart. If one employs methods suited to the land and time to aid the kingly enterprise, is this not like the right medicine for the ailment, or timely rain in drought?

    Long ago, when the Sui dynasty was about to rise while Chen and Qi stood side by side and the realm was divided three ways, there was a wise minister named Zhou Hongzheng. He counseled Emperor Wen, saying: "I have heard of a dharma gate that unites three into one, called the Wondrous Dharma Lotus Sutra. If this teaching is propagated at Gukcheongsa beneath Tiantai Mountain, the realm shall become one." The Emperor followed this counsel, and unity was indeed achieved.

    Our Eastern Han was likewise divided in three. Thus when our Great Ancestor founded his dynasty, four great monks, including Nengjiang, submitted a memorial to the imperial court: "We have heard that the Great Tang possesses the Wondrous Dharma Lotus Sutra that unites three into one, and the Tiantai Master Zhizhe's single-mind threefold observation meditation. These accord with how the sage ruler united the three Han into one nation. If we could obtain this dharma and propagate it widely, the descendants of dragons would live long, the royal enterprise would not cease, and the realm would remain forever one family."

    At that time, the opportunity was not yet ripe. But when the era of King Seonjo arrived, the king's younger brother, National Preceptor Daegeok, journeyed to Tang and returned with the teachings. He established the six mountains of Tiantai, and at the southwestern foot of Songshan, he founded a temple also called Gukcheongsa, which became the root of all six mountains. There he erected the three images of Shakyamuni Buddha as the principal figures of the hall, where the Wondrous Dharma was eternally expounded, and generations received its blessings.

    When the state fell into disorder, the temple too declined. Since its restoration, it has only begun to be rebuilt, yet the original foundation has not been recovered, and discussions have not yet reached the matter of image casting. The National Preceptor, grieving that the Buddha's seat had long remained vacant, vowed to exhaust all efforts to complete the work. A great meditation master named Er'an also contributed ten pounds of silver, but no capable person could be found to undertake the task.

    In the summer of the second year of the Huanqing era, we heard of General Lu You, whose devotion to the Three Jewels was sincere and whose administrative skill was proven. The National Preceptor entreated him to take on this work, providing over ten pounds of silver. Lu Gong joyfully accepted, swift as a stone cast into water. Indeed, in less than a month the work was complete—the towering golden image, as if emerging from the earth itself! All who saw it marveled.

    When they prepared to seal the Buddha's interior with reliquaries, more than ten clergy and laity gathered at his home. All the necessary items were ready save one: the relics. They had no place to obtain them. Sitting in mutual consternation, there arose among them a faithful devotee named Zheng Tianfu. He suddenly stood and declared: "If what the National Preceptor and all the donors have undertaken is truly virtuous, how could Buddha's relics elude our seeking?"

    Lu Gong agreed. He approached the white-robed Bodhisattva image that hung perpetually on the wall. He spread a dark silk cloth about a foot in length before it, burned incense, and prostrated three times. Raising his head to look, behold—one relic had appeared, gleaming upon the silk!

    All were startled with joy. Drawing closer to observe, they found the relics multiplying endlessly. They shone in every hue—azure, white, dark, golden—blazing brilliantly before their eyes. Lu Gong remarked, "If only there were a red one, then all five colors would be complete." Before he had finished speaking, red relics emerged—four of them! The gathered assembly wept and sighed, knowing now that the Buddha's realm admits no obstruction, that merit is never false.

    Hearing this, the National Preceptor was overcome with joy and composed a long verse in praise:

    *Three honored ones grace Gukcheongsa's hall so rare,*
    *Manjushri and Samantabhadra attend the Sage.*
    *Who gathers all conditions to accomplish this deed?*
    *General Lu Gong's virtuous endeavor.*
    *Reliquaries and treasures for the Buddha's form—*
    *One object most difficult to find: the relics themselves.*
    *The faithful Zheng Tianfu spoke to Lu Gong:*
    *"Thus the roots of good are tested true—*
    *If your devotion, patrons all, is genuine,*
    *How could obtaining relics be denied?"*
    *Lu Gong approached the white-robed image there,*
    *Spread silk and burned incense, made his vow clear,*
    *Stepped back and bowed three times low,*
    *Then raised his head to see—*
    *Already one relic on the silk appeared.*
    *All scrambled forward in delight,*
    *Within moments, countless emerged—*
    *Five colors gleaming, brilliance bright,*
    *Forms both large and small, each unique.*
    *Gathered and placed in eight-lobed reliquaries,*
    *Sealed within the Buddha trinity below.*
    *Those who heard conceived wondrous thoughts,*
    *Praise and wonder without end.*
    *Know this image is the true form itself,*
    *Unmoved by conflagration or the wind of time.*
    *All who offered even one speck to aid this work*
    *Shall surely become lords of the three realms.*

    This was a true record. When I desired to see this golden image, I visited the place where Lu Gong had sought the relics. It was a mean, cramped house by the marketplace, filled on all sides with dust and foul odors. Yet even within such humble surroundings, these miraculous signs appeared! This is truly the inconceivable power of the Buddha.

    I once read in the sutras: "The dharma body is like empty space; the dharma realm is the Buddha itself." Indeed, it is as written. If the dharma body were not one with the void—untainted by defilement, pure yet defiled-less, going nowhere, coming from nowhere—how could these relics have appeared? Here we see that form and emptiness are not two, that the pure and the impure are not separate.

    Yet I wonder: did the sincerity that drew forth these marvels rest solely upon the two worthies Lu and Zheng? Or did it also depend upon those who first made their vows and offered their wealth? I would say this is like a drum: it requires the leather, wood, mallet, and hand all present before sound can arise. So too here—some served like the leather and wood, others like the mallet and hand, but all together brought it to completion.

    When the interior was sealed and adorned, an auspicious day was chosen. On the twelfth day of the eleventh month of the first year of the Yanyou era, the image was to be enshrined at the temple. The National Preceptor, holding the incense censer, stood before the image and led the procession to the city gate. I too was summoned and joined the retinue. The wind and sun were gentle and warm as springtime. Once the image was installed, an elaborate ceremony was arranged. The next morning, as they were about to perform the ritual of the five eyes, suddenly auspicious clouds gathered from all directions, and jeweled snow danced in the air. As the dharma assembly concluded, the sky cleared and the sun shone bright.

    The National Preceptor turned to me and said, "Yesterday, when I set the time to move the image, what I feared was wind and snow. Now I merely wished for clear weather—and it cleared; I wished for snow—and it snowed. This too is a spiritual response! Seeing both the manifestation of relics days before and today's weather unfolding exactly as desired, it is clear that through these blessed conditions, our lord's life will be extended, our nation blessed, as surely as if we had made a solemn vow."

    He asked me to record this. Though my talent is meager and my brush worn, I could not refuse, as none of the other worthy scholars present were free. So I set down what I had witnessed, however imperfectly.

    The following spring, the National Preceptor reviewed what I had written and sighed deeply: "Long ago, there was the monk Kangsenghui, truly an exceptional master of all lands. When he sought relics, his purpose was to revive the great dharma. Though he endured the fearsome authority of the Wu king, he and his disciples united their strength and sincerity in supplication. Their devotion was not lacking, their effort not insufficient. Yet even after twenty-one days of intense practice, though the appointed time passed, no response came. Only after exhausting himself further and persevering through another night did he obtain a single relic.

    "Those who sought relics now are not equals of Kangsenghui, and those gathered here are but a motley throng. They have neither the discipline of a fixed vow nor the fear of punishment. Yet by merely joining palms and bowing their heads, spiritual marvels appeared a hundredfold greater! How can this be mere chance? And yet—this authentic image is housed in no proper place. How can my heart rest?"

    He again entreated Lu Gong: "Between us there must be karmic connection from past lives. Since we have together undertaken this Buddha work, would you not go further and establish a perpetual foundation, construct a reliquary chamber and diamond platform, and properly enshrine this image? Then I would have no regrets even in death." His words were earnest, and tears fell.

    Lu Gong stepped forward and replied, "Though I have passed seventy years and cannot guarantee success in all things, the master's command is supreme. How could I fail to follow with respect?" The National Preceptor then gave him all his monthly salary to undertake the work.

    With Lu Gong's acceptance, he worked alongside the abbots of Jeonglimsa and other capable craftsmen. Beginning in the third month of spring that year, the work proceeded until completion in the ninth month of autumn. The eaves and pillars seemed to dance in mid-air, while gold and blue gleamed with dazzling brilliance.

    Rejoicing at the swift completion, the National Preceptor chose an auspicious day—the fourteenth day of the tenth month—to begin a three-day ceremony. He summoned over three thousand eminent monks from the six mountains and held a grand celebration. He first performed the rituals of the Lotus Sutra of Wonderful Dharma Repentance that he himself had newly composed for the dedication.

    At midday, the royal court sent the Right Chancellor Yi Gwangsi bearing incense and candles to express imperial reverence. The National Preceptor invited the abbots of Fapuhasa to ascend the seat and preach the dharma, beseeching blessings upon the sovereign's longevity. Throughout the three days, high and low, the fourfold assembly of the city came and went, listening to teachings and forging connections, standing as thick as a wall.

    The temple possessed an ancient well, deep and large, yet its waters had been foul for some time, growing worse each day. The kitchen staff suffered greatly in drawing water for the ceremonies. When preparing this great assembly, though all offerings were gathered, water was lacking. The temple monks were greatly distressed until, three days before the ceremony, the well suddenly transformed. Its waters became crystalline and pure, with a sweet, cool taste—a miraculous occurrence!

    And three days before the assembly, the weather itself changed. Snow melted into rain that cleansed away all dust. During the three days of the ceremony, heaven remained clear and warm. On the evening the assembly concluded, rain fell in torrents—another miracle!

    Alas! Such karmic causes and conditions cannot arise without the mysterious protection of sages and the hidden aid of celestial beings. The ancient saying of Buddha and sage spirits—"When the temple is completed, the nation becomes clear"—stands as verifiable truth.

    Wishing to preserve this account alongside the earlier deeds for distant transmission, the National Preceptor commanded me to record the complete story and append it to what came before.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The Wondrous Dharma Lotus Sutra (妙法華經) refers to the Lotus Sutra, considered a central text in East Asian Buddhism, particularly important in Tiantai and Korean Buddhist traditions.
  - key: ''
    value: Tiantai Mountain and the teachings of Master Zhizhe (also known as Zhiyi) represent an important school of Buddhism that emphasized the unity of all teachings within a threefold observation of reality.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'five colors' of relics—azure, white, dark, golden, and red—represent a traditional classification in Buddhist practice, with all five colors together signifying complete spiritual attainment.
  - key: ''
    value: The reference to Kangsenghui (康僧會) alludes to a celebrated historical account of relic manifestation in Buddhist hagiography, providing a classical precedent for understanding these miraculous phenomena.
  - key: ''
    value: Gukcheongsa (國淸寺), meaning 'National Clarity Temple,' reflects the Buddhist understanding that a perfected spiritual institution brings clarity and order to the realm itself.
